{{Infobox politician | name = Francisco José Pinheiro | image = | alt = | caption = | candidate = | election_date = | runningmate = | opponent = | incumbent = | birth_date = 28 September 1954 | birth_place = [[Jaguaribe]], Brazil | death_date = | death_place = | party = | otherparty = | relations = | spouse = | civil partner = | children = | residence = | occupation = | religion = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Francisco José Pinheiro''' (born September 28, 1954 in [[Jaguaribe]], Brazil), better known as Professor Pinheiro,<ref>{{cite news|title=Ações contra diploma de deputados eleitos|url=http://diariodonordeste.globo.com/materia.asp?codigo=913182|accessdate=24 January 2011|newspaper=[[Diário do Nordeste]]|date=4 January 2011}}</ref> is a Brazilian historian, writer and politician. He was deputy governor of the state of [[Ceará]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Ceará: Assembléia dá posse ao governador eleito Cid Gomes|url=http://www.abn.com.br/editorias1.php?id=41233|accessdate=24 January 2011|newspaper=[[Agencia Bolivariana de Noticias]]|date=2 January 2007|language=Portuguese}}</ref> (one of Brazil's states in the [[Northeast Region, Brazil|northeast region]]), in the first term of Governor [[Cid Gomes]]. Today was elected state representative, but took over as head of the Secretary of Culture of the state of Ceará.
==Education== Professor Pinheiro has a PhD in [[social history]] from the [[Universidade de Pernambuco|University of Pernambuco]]. He is a history professor at the [[Universidade Federal do Ceará|Federal University of Ceará]] (UFC) and a specialist in [[History of the Roman Catholic Church|history of the Catholic Church]] in [[Latin America]] at the [[Pontifical Catholic University of São Paulo]] (PUC-SP).
==Career== He was president of the professors’ union at UFC, councilman in [[Fortaleza]] (Ceará's capital), and twice president of Fortaleza’s [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Workers' Party]] (PT). He was also secretary of region IV in Fortaleza, during mayor [[Luizianne Lins]]' first administration.
==Personal life== He is married to Margarida de Lima Pompeu, a doctor and professor of Pathology and Forensic Medicine at UFC. The couple have four children: Heráclito Aragão Pinheiro, Francisco Pablo H. Aragão Pinheiro, Iago Domingos Menezes Pinheiro, and Alfa Manuela Pompeu Pinheiro.
