The '''Gladstone Chair of Greek''' is an academic position that was one of the original endowments of the foundation of the [[University of Liverpool]] in 1881. The [[professorship|Chair]] was named in recognition of the scholarship of [[W. E. Gladstone]], the British [[prime minister]], and the close association of the Gladstone family with [[Liverpool]].<ref>[http://www.liv.ac.uk/commsec/calendar/University%20Chairs%20and%20their%20Holders%20Past%20and%20Present%202009-10.pdf University Chairs and their Holders Past and Present]{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
With the decline in the teaching of [[Classics]] the chair has been vacant since [[A. A. Long|Professor Long]] left in 1983 to take up a position in the United States.
==Gladstone Professors of Greek== * 1891–1898 [[Gerald Henry Rendall]] * 1898–1906 [[Gilbert Austin Davies]] * 1907–1910 [[John Myres|Sir John Lynton Myres]] * 1911–1914 [[:de:Carl Ferdinand Friedrich Lehmann-Haupt|Carl Friedrich Ferdinand Lehmann-Haupt]] * 1919–1921 [[Alfred Chilton Pearson]] (subsequently [[Regius Professor of Greek (Cambridge)|Regius Professor of Greek]] at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge University]]) * 1922–1950 [[A. Y. Campbell|Archibald Young Campbell]] * 1950–1972 [[A. H. Armstrong|Arthur Hilary Armstrong]] * 1973–1983 [[A. A. Long|Anthony Arthur Long]]
