{{History of Romania}}
{{For|earlier events|Prehistory of Romania|Prehistory of Transylvania}}
This section of the [[timeline of Romanian history]] concerns events from [[Late Neolithic]] (c. 3900 BC) till [[Late Antiquity]] (c. 400 AD), who took place in or are directly related with the territory of modern [[Romania]].

== Late Neolithic and Bronze Age (3800 – 1200  BC) ==
{{Main|Bronze Age in Romania}}
{{For|earlier events|Prehistory of Romania|Prehistory of Transylvania}}

=== 4th millennium BC ===
* 3900 BC – [[Bodrogkeresztúr-Gorneşti culture]] begins in Transylvania, as a continuation of [[Petreşti culture]]
* 3700 BC – [[Cernavodă III culture]] begins in [[Danube Valley]], as a continuation of [[Cernavodă I culture]]
* 3500 BC – [[Copper Age]] begins and the areas of cultural influence start to expand again but without reaching the size of early [[Neolithic]]{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
* 3500 BC – [[Cernavodă III culture]] begins in Dobruja, as a continuation of [[Cernavodă I culture]]
* 3500 BC – [[Coţofeni culture]] begins in Transylvania as a continuation of [[Bodrogkeresztúr-Gorneşti culture]]
* 3500 BC – [[Baden culture]] begins in [[Lower Tisza]]/[[Crişana]] as a continuation of [[Bodrogkeresztúr-Gorneşti culture]]

=== 3rd millennium BC ===
* 3000-2800 BC – Climate becomes hotter and drier, affecting the human societies{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
* 2750 BC – [[Cucuteni culture]] in eastern Romania [[Decline and end of the Cucuteni–Trypillian culture|comes to an end]]
* 2700 BC – Transition from [[Copper Age]] to [[Bronze Age]]{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Proto-Indo-Europeans]] related to the [[Decea Mureşului culture]] penetrate in Transylvania coming from the [[Black Sea]] region{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Kostolac culture]] develops sporadically in [[Banat]] coming from modern day [[Serbia]]{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Vučedol culture]] (3000 – 2200 BC) develops in [[Banat]] and western [[Crişana]] also coming from [[Serbia]]{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
* 2700-2000 BC – Proto-Indo-Europeans assimilate the local [[Eneolithic]] populations
* 2300-1900 BC – [[Verbicioara culture]] develops in [[Oltenia]], [[Banat]] and western [[Muntenia]]<ref>http://www.verticalonline.ro/cultura-verbicioara-si-locatiile-sale-iv</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.archaeology.ro/imc_verb.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317115249/http://www.archaeology.ro/imc_verb.htm |archivedate=2012-03-17 |df= }}</ref>
* 2100 BC – [[Otomani culture]] develops from a Baden culure background in a widespread area among Mureş, the Apuseni Mountains and Tisa up to modern-day Slovakia; characterized by fortified settlements and islands, the bronze deposits from [[Apa, Satu Mare|Apa]], [[Valea Chioarului]] in Transylvania and Haidu Samson in Hungary, the typical full handle swords and the axes with disc, the practice of inhumation, and later of cremation, and with the sanctuary of [[Sălacea]]{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}

=== 2nd millennium BC ===
[[File:Alba Iulia National Museum of the Union 2011 - Pottery, Bone and Bronze Artefacts of the Wietenberg Culture.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Pottery, bone and bronze artefacts of the [[Wietenberg culture]]. In display at [[National Museum of the Union]], Alba Iulia]]
* 2000 BC – [[Early Bronze Age]] starts{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** Due to its richness in copper, Transylvania becomes one of the most important metallurgical centers in Europe{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Nir culture]] develops{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Glina III-Schneckenberg culture]] develops in [[Muntenia]] and extends into [[Oltenia]] and south eastern Transylvania{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}; it is characterized by settlements on any terrain, and the practices of [[inhumation]] and incinerations in [[cist]]s{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
* 2000-1800 BC – [[Cucuteni B culture]] destroyed{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* 1700 BC
** [[Glina culture]] begins in [[Muntenia]] and [[Oltenia]]
** [[Otomani culture]] ends in [[Crişana]]
* 1700-1300 BC [[Monteoru culture]] begins {{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* 1600 BC – [[Gârla Mare culture]] begins in [[Oltenia]]<ref>https://www.scribd.com/doc/42790157/Cultura-Garla-Mare</ref>
* 1500 BC – [[Middle Bronze Age]] starts{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Periam culture]] develops in southern Crişana, Banat, north-eastern Serbia and western Bulgaria; characterized by bronze jewelery and the practice of inhumation{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Pecica culture]] appears as a continuation of Periam culture and expands into the middle Danube, [[Tisza|Tisa]], and lower [[Mureș (river)|Mureş]]; brings [[moulds]] for [[casting]] weapons, crouched inhumation and the gold treasures from [[Pecica]] and Rovine{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Periam-Pecica/Mureş culture]]
** [[Sighişoara-Wietenberg culture]] develops from a [[Coţofeni culture]] background in the center and the [[Transylvanian Plain]]; characterized by fortified settlements with many weapons, pottery with spiral and [[Meander (art)|meander]] motifs, bronze deposits, Boiu-type swords, [[Mycenaean Greece|Mycenaean]] swords from import, golden jewellery and axes ([[Ţufalău]]), the practice of cremation and much rarely of inhumation{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Vatina culture]] begins in western [[Banat]], on lower [[Tisza|Tisa]] and northern Serbia; defined by rare bronze objects{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Verbicioara culture]] expands into Oltenia, eastern Muntenia, Serbia and north-western Bulgaria, with fortified settlements and a limited number of bronze artefacts{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Monteoru culture]] expands from Muntenia into south-eastern Transylvania{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Tei culture]]  expands from Muntenia into south-eastern Transylvania{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Suciu de Sus culture]] spreads into northern Transylvania, Crisana, north-eastern Hungary and south-eastern Slovakia, practicing cremation{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Cruceni-Belegiš culture]] follows and replaces the Vatina culture in Serbia and western Banat; it is part of the [[Urnfield culture]] which moves from the middle Danube towards south-east; this advance leads to great dislocations of populations in the [[Balkan Peninsula]], resulting in [[Dorian invasion|Dorian migration]] to the south, the destruction of [[Mycenaean civilization]] and expeditions of the [[Sea Peoples]]{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
* 1300 BC – [[Late Bronze Age]] starts{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** [[Sighişoara-Wietenberg culture]] extends into south-eastern Transylvania{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
** Tribes of shepherds appear from the east as the [[Noua culture]]; characterized by bronze deposits of [[Uriu]]-[[Domăneşti]] type and metal working{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|pp=63-114}}
* 1250-1125 BC – Transition to [[Iron Age]]: [[Uioara de Sus]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}

== Iron Age (1200 BC – 400 AD) ==

=== 12th century BC ===
* 1200-500 BC – [[Early Iron Age]]/[[Hallstatt culture]] : [[Ferigile]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* 1150 BC – [[Gârla Mare culture]] ends in [[Oltenia]]<ref>https://www.scribd.com/doc/42790157/Cultura-Garla-Mare</ref>

=== 9th century BC ===
* 900-800 BC – [[Rafaila]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* c. 800 BC – [[Basarabi culture]] begins in [[Muntenia]], in connection with the [[Bosut culture]], ethnically identified with [[Triballi]]<ref>Predrag Medović, Praistorija na tlu Vojvodine, Novi Sad, 2001, pages 129-130.</ref> or [[Dacians|Daco]]-[[Getae]]s.<ref>Dragoslav Srejović, Iliri i Tračani, Beograd, 2002, page 243.</ref><ref name="vulpe1967">Alexandru Vulpe- Necropola hallstattiana de la Ferigile, Bucuresti, 1967</ref>

=== 8th century BC ===
{{Main|Scythians|Agathyrsi}}
* 700-500 BC – [[Poiana, Galaţi]] ([[Piroboridava]]){{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* c. 700 BC – [[Scythians]] arrive in the [[Carpathians]]<ref name="Parvan (1928) 48 ">Parvan (1928) 48</ref>

=== 7th century BC ===
* c. 600 BC – [[Basarabi culture]] ends, possibly due to arrival of the [[Scythian]] tribes<ref>http://scindeks.nb.rs/article.aspx?artid=0350-76530535007T</ref><ref name="guma">Marian Gumă- Civilizaţia primei epoci a fierului în sud-vestul României, Bucureşti, 1993</ref>
* 657 BC or 625 BC – [[Histria (ancient city)|Histria]] founded{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}

=== 6th century BC ===
{{Main|Scythians|Agathyrsi|Getae|Greek colonies in Dacia}}
[[File:Alba Iulia National Museum of the Union 2011 - Offering pot from a Scythian Grave.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Offering pot from a [[Scythian]] grave from [[Alba Iulia]], Romania, 6th century BC. In display at [[National Museum of the Union]], Alba Iulia]]
* 6th-5th century BC
** Tomis is founded{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
** Histria, temple of [[Zeus Polieus]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* 560 BC – [[Megara]] founds [[Heraclea Pontica]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
** Callatis founded{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}} by [[Heraclea Pontica]], itself a colony of [[Megara]]
* c. 550 BC – [[Agathyrsi]], a [[Thraco-Scythian]] people, build burial tombs around modern day [[Ciumbrud]], in contrast with the surrounding people who practice incineration<ref name="Parvan (1928) 48 " /><ref name=" Thomson (1948) 399">Thomson (1948) 399</ref>
* 514 BC – [[Darius I]] led his Persian army over the [[Bosphorus]] and campaigns unsuccessfully against the [[Scythians]] on the [[Danube]].
* 513 BC – Darius subdues the [[Getae]] and east [[Thrace]] in his war against the [[Scythians]].
* 513 BC – first written evidence of tribes ([[Getae]] or [[Dacians]]) inhabiting the region by [[Herodotus]]

=== 5th century BC ===
{{Main|Scythians|Getae|Greek colonies in Dacia}}

[[File:ScytianBowl.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Scythian [[Bowl (vessel)|bowl]], 5th century BC found at [[Castelu]], [[Romania]]. In display at [[Constanţa Museum of National History]]]]
* 500 – 1 BC – [[Middle Iron Age]]/[[La Tène culture]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* 5th-4th century BC – A [[Getic]] settlement is found at [[Zimnicea]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* 470 – 460 – The king [[Charnabon]] reigns over the Getae {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* c. 450 BC – [[Democracy]] is imposed in Histria{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=215}}
* 431 – 424 – [[Odrysian]] king [[Sitalces]] conquests the territory of modern [[Dobruja]] ruling over the local Getic tribes {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}

=== 4th century BC ===
{{Main|Getae|Dacians|Celts in Transylvania|Greek colonies in Dacia}}

* [[Agighiol]] silver treasure{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* [[Golden Helmet of Coţofeneşti]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* Callatis wall{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* Callatis papyrus grave{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 364/363-353/352 BC – [[Clearchus of Heraclea|Clearchus]], [[tyrant]] of Heraclea Pontica{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 341 – King [[Cothelas]], also known as Gudila, ruled over the Geto-Dacian tribes from modern Dobruja {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* 348 BC – Philip II of Macedon against Thracians{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 339 BC – Philip II against Scythians{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}} led by [[Ateas]]{{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* 339 BC – A Getic ruler, referred as "Histrianorum Rex" and located near Danube, opposes resistance to Ateas' Scythian army {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* 335 BC – [[Alexander III of Macedon]] crosses the Danube{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}} fighting with Dacian tribes led by [[basileus]] [[Moskon]]{{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* c. 335 BC – [[Dacian king]] [[Sarmis]]/[[Armis]] rules in Transylvania {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* 326 BC – The Macedon general [[Zopyrion]] leads a campaign north of [[Black Sea]] against Getae but he is defeated and ultimately killed {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* 313 BC – Histria revolts against [[Lysimachus]] of Thrace{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 310-309 BC – Lysimachus besieges Callatis{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* late 4th century BC
** Histria, sacred area burnt{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
** Callatis, ustrinum{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 4th-2nd century BC
** Histria, [[Hellenistic]] wall {{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
** Callatis, gilt terra-cotta miniatures{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}

=== 3rd century BC ===
{{Main|Dacians|Getae|Celts in Transylvania}}

* King [[Zalmodegikos]] rules over Dobruja {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* [[Celts]] migrate to Transilvania and [[Oltenia]] {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* [[Poroina]] rython{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* Histria, temple of Aphrodite{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* [[Piscul Crăsanilor]], Dacian settlement{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* King [[Dromichaites]] rules over tribal unions in [[Romanian Plain]] {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* 297 BC – Lysimachus make peace with Dromichaites {{sfn|Bârsan|2013}}
* 292 BC – Lysimachus fight against Getae and he is defeated{{sfn|Bârsan|2013}} and taken prisoner, perhaps in Piscul Crăsanilor
* 281 BC – Lysimachus dies{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 279 BC – Celts attack Histria and [[Delphi]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 262 BC – Histria and Callatis war against [[Byzantium]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 251 BC – Theoros from Callatis{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 230-130 BC – [[Ciumeşti]] necropolis{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}

=== 2nd century BC ===
{{Main|Dacia|Celts in Transylvania|Oroles}}

* first half of 2nd century BC – the [[Dacia]]n Kingdom was led by King [[Oroles]]
* 200 BC – Callatis building inscription{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 200-150 BC – Histria ephebe inscription{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 2nd century? - Histria aqueduct{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 2nd-1st century BC – Popeşti flourishes{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 145-172 BC – [[Tilişca]] counterfeiter's coins{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 110-72/71 BC – Mithridates controls Pontic cities{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 109 BC – Dacians togher with [[Scordisci]] attack Roman provinces situated south of Danube; attack repelled by [[M. Minucius Rufus]] {{sfn|Giugrascu|1972|p=24}}

=== 1st century BC ===
{{Main|Dacia|Burebista}}

[[File:Burebista statue in Orastie.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Modern statue of the Dacian King [[Burebista]] (ruled 82-44 BC) in [[Orăştie]], [[Romania]]]]
* 82 BC  – [[Burebista]] unifies the [[Dacians]] and [[Getae]] forming the first and largest [[Dacian Kingdom]], on the territory of modern Romania and surroundings{{sfn|Daicoviciu|1991|p=68}}
* early 80s BC – Burebista moves capital from Popeşti to Costeşti{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 80 BC – 106 AD – Dacian citadels{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 74 BC – [[Dacian Kingdom]] at its peak under King [[Burebista]]
* 72-71 BC – War between Pontic cities, allied with Thracians, and Romans; Callatis treaty with Rome{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}{{sfn|Giugrascu|1972|p=26}}
* 61 BC – Coalition of Greeks and barbarians (Getae and [[Bastarnae]]) defeats [[C. Antonius Hybrida]] at Histria{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}{{sfn|Giugrascu|1972|p=26}}
* c. 60 BC – Burebista leads a policy of conquest of new territories: he attacks and vanquishes the [[Celts|Celtic]] tribes of [[Boii]] and [[Taurisci]] dwelling along the [[Middle Danube]] (in what is now [[Slovakia]]){{sfn|Pippidi|1976|p=116-117}}
* c. 57 BC –  Burebista conquers the [[Black Sea]] shore, subjugating the Greek fortresses from [[Olbia]] to [[Apollonia, Thrace|Apollonia]], as well as the [[Danubian Flat|Danubian Plain]] all the way to the [[Balkans]].{{sfn|Pippidi|1976|p=116-117}}
* Burebista runs expeditions against a group of Celts who lived among the Thracians and Illyrians (probably the [[Scordisci]]){{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3,11}}}<ref name="koch">John T. Koch, ''Celtic culture: a historical encyclopedia'', p.550, ABC-CLIO, 2006 {{ISBN|1851094407}}</ref>
[[File:Costesti Cetatuie Dacian Fortress 2011 - Tower House One and Stairs-4.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Tower house one and staircase with drain at the [[Dacian fortress of Costeşti]]]]
* after 50 BC – Histria, "second founding"{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}
* 48 BC – Burebista sides with [[Pompey]] during his struggle against [[Julius Caesar]] in the [[Great Roman Civil War]] (49–45 BC){{sfn|Pippidi|1976|p=116-117}}, sending [[Akornion]] as an ambassador and a military adviser{{sfn|Daicoviciu|1991|p=65}}
* 48 BC – Citizens of [[Dionysopolis]] dedicate an inscription to [[Akornion]], which mention this citizens' friendship to [[Burebista]]{{sfn|Daicoviciu|1991|p=65}}, as well as a diplomatic mission to the Dacian town named [[Argedava]]{{sfn|Daicoviciu|1991|p=67}} or [[Argidava]]{{sfn|Crişan|1978|p=61}} to possibly visit Burebista's father{{sfn|Daicoviciu|1991|p=67}}
* c. 45 BC – Caesar emerges as victor and plans on sending legions to punish Burebista{{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3,5}}
* 44 BC
** On March 15 Caesar is assassinated in the [[Roman Senate|Senate]] before he can start a campaign against the Dacian Kingdom
** Burebista is assassinated{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}} in a plot made by the tribal aristocracy, which felt that a consolidation towards a centralized state would reduce their power
** The Dacian Kingdom is dissolved, with the exception of the nucleus around the [[Orăştie Mountains]],{{sfn|Pippidi|1976|p=116-117}} while the rest being divided into four different kingdoms{{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3,11}}
* 42 BC – [[Dacians|Geto-Dacian]] contingent with [[Marcus Junius Brutus|Brutus]] at the [[Battle of Philippi]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=216}}, fighting against [[Augustus|Octavian]] and [[Mark Antony]]
* 27 BC – Crassus triumphs over Geto-Dacians{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* [[Augustus Caesar]] sends an army against the [[Dacians|Geto-Dacians]], finding the former state of Burebista divided into five states{{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3,11}}
* 14 BC – 98 AD – Minor Dacian citadels flourish{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}

=== 1st century ===
{{Main|Dacia|Decebalus|Domitian's Dacian War}}

[[File:Statue of Roman poet Ovid in Constanţa, Romania.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Statue of Roman poet [[Ovid]] in [[Constanţa]] (ancient Tomis, the city where he was exiled). Created in 1887 by the Italian sculptor [[Ettore Ferrari]]]]
* 6-12 AD – [[Sextus Aelius Catus]] destroys Muntenian towns{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 9-17 AD – [[Ovid]] in exile at [[Constanța|Tomis]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 12 AD – Getae from Lower Moldavia attack [[Aegyssus]] and capture it temporarily; attack repelled by [[Odrysian]] king [[Rhoemetalces I]] and [[P. Vitellius]] {{sfn|Giugrascu|1972|p=24}}
* 14 AD
** Barbarians attack [[Troesmis]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
** [[Dobruja]] becomes province of [[Moesia]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 15-35 AD – [[C. Poppaeus Sabinus]], governor of Moesia{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* c. 20 AD – [[Strabo]] publishes his ''[[Geographica]]'' (Geography) giving a detailed account of the [[Dacian Kingdom]] at the time of [[Burebista]] in ''Book VII, Chapter 3 (Mysia, Dacia, and the Danube)''{{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3}}; he mentions that [[Getae]] and [[Dacians]] speak the same language{{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3,12}}, and makes important references to the high priest [[Deceneus]] and the teachings of [[Zalmoxis]]{{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3,5}}{{sfn|Strabo|20 AD|loc=VII 3,11}}
* 26 AD – [[Poppaeus Sabinus]] and [[L. Pomponius Flaccus]] crushes Dobrujan revolt of Thracians {{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}{{sfn|Giugrascu|1972|p=29}}
* c. 49 AD – Histria's fishing rights guaranteed{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 54-68 AD – [[Noviodunum]] camp founded, during [[Nero]]'s reign{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 57-67 AD – [[Tiberius Plautius Silvanus Aelianus]], governor of Moesia{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 60-65 AD – [[Columella]], agricultural writer, flourishes{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 69 AD – Invasion of Dacians and [[Roxolans]] in Moesia, south of Danube; response of governor [[M. Aponinus Saturninus]] {{sfn|Giugrascu|1972|p=29}}
* c. 77 AD –  [[Pliny the Elder]] publishes his ''[[Naturalis Historia]]'' (Natural History), gives an account of the Dacians, noting that the Romans call the ''Getae'', ''Daci''{{sfn|Pliny the Elder|77 AD|loc=IV 25}}
* 81-96 AD – [[Castra of Tirighina-Bărboși|Bărboşi]] naval base founded during Domitian's reign{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* before 84 AD – [[Duras (Dacian king)|Duras]] becomes [[List of Dacian kings|King of the Dacians]] and consolidates the consolidate the core of Dacia around [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmizegetusa]]
* 84 AD – [[Diurpaneus]] reorganizes the Dacian army, and begins minor raids upon the heavily fortified [[Roman province]] of [[Moesia]], on the southern course of the [[Danube]] river
* 85 AD
** King Duras orders more vigorous attacks into [[Moesia]], raids being led by [[Diurpaneus]]
** Led by [[Diurpaneus]] the Dacians cross the [[Danube]], wreak considerable havoc and kill the Moesian governor [[Oppius Sabinus]].{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=138}}
** After this attack, the Roman emperor [[Domitian]] personally arrives in Moesia accompanied by a large force commanded by [[Cornelius Fuscus]], and possibly bases himself in [[Naissus]]{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=138}}
** Summer 85 AD – [[Praetorian prefect]] Fuscus  and [[Funisulanus Vettonianus]] successfully drives the Dacians back across the border{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=139}}{{sfn|Giugrascu|1972|p=24}}
** Autumn 85 AD – Domitian returns to Rome and celebrates the tenth and eleventh salutations for driving out the invaders{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=139}}
* 85-89 AD – [[Hadrian]] commands [[Legio V Macedonica]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 86 AD
** Domitian celebrates a [[Roman triumph|triumph]] in Rome between March 17 and May 15 for the victory over the Dacians{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=139}}
** Domitian reorganizes the province of Moesia into [[Moesia Inferior]] and [[Moesia Superior]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}, and plans a future attack into [[Dacia]].
* 87 AD
** Cornelius Fuscus leads five or six legions across the Danube into [[Dacia]] on a bridge of ships<ref name="Romanis REquote01">{{cite web
|accessdate=2007-11-08
|url=http://www.roman-emperors.org/assobd.htm#t-inx
|title=De Imperatoribus Romanis
|work=An Online Encyclopedia of Roman Emperors
|format=Assorted Imperial Battle Descriptions
|quote= Battle of Sarmizegetusa (Sarmizegetuza), A.D. 105. During Trajan's reign one of the most important Roman successes was the victory over the Dacians. The first important confrontation between the Romans and the Dacians took place in the year 87 and was initiated by Domitian. The [[praetorian prefect]] [[Cornelius Fuscus|Cornelius]] led five or six legions across the Danube on a bridge of ships and advanced towards [[Banat]] (in Romania). The Romans were surprised by a Dacian attack at Tapae (near the village of [[Bucova]], in Romania). Legion V Alaude was crushed and Cornelius Fuscus was killed. The victorious general was originally known as [[Diurpaneus]] (see Manea, p.109), but after this victory he was called Decebalus (the brave one).}}</ref>
** The [[Roman legion]]s are ambushed at [[Tapae]] and face disaster with complete destruction of [[Legio V Alaudae]] (see [[First Battle of Tapae]]){{sfn|Jones|1992|p=141}}
** Cornelius Fuscus dies in the battle{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}, the [[Aquila (Roman)|battle standard]] of the Praetorian Guard is lost and the Dacians capture Roman flags and war machines{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=141}}
** [[Ancient Rome|Rome]] must pay [[tribute]] to the [[Dacians]] in exchange for a vague recognition of Rome's importance.
** King Duras knowingly offers the kingship to [[Diurpaneus]] as a recognition of his diplomatic, military and leadership skills
** Diurpaneus dubbs himself [[Decebalus]], meaning "with the strength of ten [men]"<ref>"Decebalus" means "strong as ten [men]" (cf. [[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]] ''daśabala''); ''Dece-'' being derived from [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] ''*dekm-'' ('ten') and ''-balus'' from PIE ''*bel-'', 'strong'. Cf. [[Albanian language|Proto-Albanian]] ''*dek(a)t-'', from PIE ''*dekm-'' (Demiraj, 1999).</ref> or simply "The Brave,"<ref name="Romanis REquote01" /> and is crowned king of Dacia
* 88 AD
** The Roman offensive into Dacia continues, with general [[Tettius Iulianus]] in command{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=142}}
** The army starts from [[Viminacium]] following the same route Cornelius Fuscus had in the previous year and heads towards [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmizegetusa]], the capital of Dacia{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=142}}
** In Rome, Domitian celebrates the [[Secular Games]] and possibly plans a trip to the Danube to accept Dacians' surrender in person{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=142}}
** Late 88, a battle takes place mainly in the same area, at [[Tapae]], and this time the Romans are victorious{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=142}}
** Facing a difficult road to [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmizegetusa]] and for fear of falling into a trap, Iulianus abandons the offensive<ref name="Romanis REquote01" />
** Decebalus sues for peace but Domitian refuses<ref name="Romanis REquote01" />
* 89 AD
** Domitian attacks the Germanic [[Suebi]] tribes of [[Marcomanni]] and [[Quadi]], possibly as a punitive action since the [[Germanics]] did not provide assistance in the Dacian conflict{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=151}}
** After [[Marcomanni]] defeat the Romans in [[Pannonia]] and Rome faces wars on two fronts, Domitian comes in person to the [[Danube]] and accepts the peace with the Dacians{{sfn|Jones|1992|pp=150-151}}
** Later in the year, Decebalus sends [[Diegis]], general, member of the Dacian royal family and brother of Decebalus{{sfn|Martial|100 AD|loc=5.3}}, to Rome{{sfn|Martial|100 AD|loc=5.3}} to accept the [[diadem]] from Domitian and the generous settlement{{sfn|Jones|1992|pp=150-151}}
** Decebalus becomes a [[client state|client king]] of [[Ancient Rome|Rome]], he receives money, [[Artisan|craftsmen]]{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=150}} and [[Siege engine|war machines]] to protect the empire's borders
** For Domitians' achievements in Dacia, the [[Roman Senate]] decrees a huge equestrian statue, impressive games take places and throughout the empire statues are erected{{sfn|Jones|1992|p=151}}
* after 89 AD
** Instead of using the money as Rome intended, Decebalus builds [[Dacian Fortresses of the Orăștie Mountains|new citadels in the mountains]], in important strategic points, and reinforces the existing ones.
* 92 AD
** A coalition of [[Dacians]] and [[Rhoxolani]] Sarmatians completely slaughter the [[Legio XXI Rapax|Legio XXI ''Rapax'']] at [[Tropaeum Traiani]], modern [[Romania]], in the [[Battle of Adamclisi (92 AD)|First Battle of Adamclisi]]
** Angustia diploma{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=217}}
* 96 AD – In September, Domitian is assassinated, one potential reason being the unfavorable peace with [[Decebalus]]

=== 2nd century ===
{{Main|Dacia|Decebalus|Trajan's Dacian Wars|Roman Dacia}}

* 101-102 AD – [[First Dacian War|first campaign]] of Emperor [[Trajan]] against [[Dacians]]{{sfn|MacKendrick|2000|p=218}}
